            <p class="text-xl text-gray-600 max-w-3xl mx-auto">Why does a cup of hot chocolate feel warm and an ice cream feel cold? It's all about heat and temperature! Let's investigate how heat moves and how we measure it.</p>
        </section>

        <!-- Lesson Section -->
        <section id="lesson" class="mb-16">
            <h2 class="text-4xl font-bold text-center mb-10">Heat vs. Temperature</h2>
            <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-8 max-w-5xl mx-auto mb-12">
                <!-- Heat -->
                <div class="card bg-orange-50 border-orange-200">
                    <h3 class="text-3xl font-semibold mb-4 text-orange-800">üî• Heat</h3>
                    <p class="mb-4">Heat is a type of <span class="font-bold">energy</span>. It's the energy that makes things feel warm. When you heat something up, you are adding energy to it!</p>
                </div>

                <!-- Temperature -->
                <div class="card bg-sky-50 border-sky-200">
                    <h3 class="text-3xl font-semibold mb-4 text-sky-800">üå°Ô∏è Temperature</h3>
                    <p class="mb-4">Temperature is the <span class="font-bold">measurement</span> of how hot or cold something is. We use a thermometer to measure it in degrees, like Celsius (¬∞C).</p>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <h2 class="text-4xl font-bold text-center mb-10">How Heat Travels</h2>
            <div class="grid md:grid-cols-3 gap-8">
                <!-- Conduction -->
                <div class="card">
                    <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold mb-4 text-purple-800">ü§ù Conduction (By Touch)</h3>
                    <p>This is when heat travels through something solid. Imagine a metal spoon in a cup of hot soup. The heat travels up the spoon from particle to particle until the handle feels warm.</p>
                    <p class="mt-4 font-semibold">Examples: A hot pan on the stove, your hand warming up a cold glass.</p>
                </div>

                <!-- Convection -->
                <div class="card">
                    <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold mb-4 text-green-800">üí® Convection (By Flow)</h3>
                    <p>This is how heat moves through liquids and gases. When you boil water, the hot water at the bottom rises, and the cooler water at the top sinks to get heated. This creates a circular flow called a convection current.</p>
                     <p class="mt-4 font-semibold">Examples: Boiling water, wind (sea breeze/land breeze).</p>
                </div>
                
                <!-- Radiation -->
                <div class="card">
                    <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold mb-4 text-yellow-800">‚òÄÔ∏è Radiation (By Waves)</h3>
                    <p>This is heat that travels in waves through space. It doesn't need anything to touch! It's how we feel the warmth of the sun, even though it's millions of kilometers away.</p>
                     <p class="mt-4 font-semibold">Examples: The Sun's warmth, heat from a campfire.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

             <!-- Key Temperatures -->
             <div class="card max-w-4xl mx-auto mt-12">
                 <h3 class="text-3xl font-semibold mb-4 text-center">Important Temperatures to Know</h3>
                <div class="flex justify-around text-center">
                    <div>
                        <p class="text-5xl font-bold text-sky-600">0¬∞C</p>
                        <p class="text-lg">Freezing Point of Water</p>
                        <p>(When water turns into solid ice)</p>
                    </div>
                     <div>
                        <p class="text-5xl font-bold text-red-600">100¬∞C</p>
                        <p class="text-lg">Boiling Point of Water</p>
                        <p>(When water turns into gas/steam)</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

